---
import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout title="RTCM">
  <section class="section">
    <div class="container learn-container">

      <nav class="breadcrumb">
        <a href="/learn">Learn</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <a href="/learn/protocols">Protocols</a>
        <span>›</span>
        <span>RTCM</span>
      </nav>

      <div class="article-header">
        <span class="badge">Protocols · Article 3 of 5</span>
        <h1>RTCM</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          RTCM SC-104 is the standard for transmitting GNSS correction data between reference
          stations and rovers. It carries everything from simple pseudorange corrections for
          DGNSS to full carrier-phase observations for RTK and State Space Representation
          corrections for PPP-RTK. If your receiver uses network corrections, it is almost
          certainly receiving RTCM.
        </p>
        <div class="article-meta">
          <span>12 min read</span>
          <span>·</span>
          <span>Last updated March 2026</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="toc">
        <div class="toc-title">Contents</div>
        <ol>
          <li><a href="#overview">Overview</a></li>
          <li><a href="#frame-structure">Frame structure</a></li>
          <li><a href="#legacy">Legacy messages (RTCM 2.x)</a></li>
          <li><a href="#rtcm3">RTCM 3.x — the modern standard</a></li>
          <li><a href="#msm">MSM — Multiple Signal Messages</a></li>
          <li><a href="#ssr">SSR — State Space Representation</a></li>
          <li><a href="#common-messages">Common message reference</a></li>
          <li><a href="#choosing">Choosing which messages to output</a></li>
          <li><a href="#summary">Summary</a></li>
          <li><a href="#references">References</a></li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 1 -->
      <h2 id="overview">Overview</h2>
      <p>
        RTCM stands for <strong>Radio Technical Commission for Maritime Services</strong> —
        the standards body that originally developed these protocols for maritime DGNSS in the
        early 1990s. The standard has evolved far beyond its maritime origins and is now the
        universal correction format used by virtually every GNSS correction service in the world.
      </p>
      <p>
        Unlike NMEA (ASCII text) and RINEX (plain text files), RTCM is a <strong>compact binary
        protocol</strong>. This makes it efficient for real-time transmission over low-bandwidth
        links — a complete RTK observation set for 10 satellites can fit in a few hundred bytes
        per second.
      </p>

      <div class="overview-cards">
        <div class="ov-card">
          <div class="ov-icon">📡</div>
          <div class="ov-title">What it carries</div>
          <div class="ov-desc">Reference station observations, pseudorange corrections, RTK carrier phase data, precise orbit/clock corrections (SSR), antenna information.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ov-card">
          <div class="ov-icon">🔢</div>
          <div class="ov-title">Format</div>
          <div class="ov-desc">Binary, variable-length frames. Not human-readable. Compact — suitable for 9600 bps radio modems, cellular data, NTRIP streams.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="ov-card">
          <div class="ov-icon">🌐</div>
          <div class="ov-title">Transport</div>
          <div class="ov-desc">Serial cable, UHF/VHF radio modem, internet via NTRIP, satellite L-band broadcast. The data is the same regardless of transport layer.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 2 -->
      <h2 id="frame-structure">Frame structure</h2>
      <p>
        Every RTCM 3.x message uses the same framing regardless of message type:
      </p>

      <div class="frame-diagram">
        <div class="frame-byte preamble">
          <div class="fb-label">Preamble</div>
          <div class="fb-bits">8 bits</div>
          <div class="fb-val">0xD3</div>
          <div class="fb-desc">Always 0xD3. Used for synchronisation.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="frame-byte reserved">
          <div class="fb-label">Reserved</div>
          <div class="fb-bits">6 bits</div>
          <div class="fb-val">000000</div>
          <div class="fb-desc">Reserved, set to zero.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="frame-byte length">
          <div class="fb-label">Message length</div>
          <div class="fb-bits">10 bits</div>
          <div class="fb-val">0–1023</div>
          <div class="fb-desc">Number of bytes in the data payload. Max 1023 bytes.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="frame-byte data">
          <div class="fb-label">Data payload</div>
          <div class="fb-bits">variable</div>
          <div class="fb-val">message type + data</div>
          <div class="fb-desc">First 12 bits = message type number (1–4095). Followed by message-specific fields.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="frame-byte crc">
          <div class="fb-label">CRC-24Q</div>
          <div class="fb-bits">24 bits</div>
          <div class="fb-val">3 bytes</div>
          <div class="fb-desc">Qualcomm CRC-24 over preamble + reserved + length + data. Always verify before processing.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">🔒</div>
        <div>
          <strong>CRC-24Q:</strong> The CRC polynomial is 0x1864CFB (25 bits). In a receiver parsing
          RTCM, always compute and verify the CRC before processing the payload.
          On noisy radio links, corrupt frames are common — a bad CRC means discard the frame.
          Do not process RTCM frames without CRC validation.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 3 -->
      <h2 id="legacy">Legacy messages (RTCM 2.x)</h2>
      <p>
        RTCM 2.x messages were designed in the early 1990s for GPS-only DGNSS over low-bandwidth
        radio links. They are largely obsolete but you may encounter them with older equipment:
      </p>

      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Message</th><th>Content</th><th>Use</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><strong>Type 1</strong></td><td>Differential GPS corrections (PRC, RRC)</td><td>Code DGNSS — the original RTCM message</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Type 2</strong></td><td>Delta differential corrections</td><td>Update to type 1 corrections</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Type 3</strong></td><td>Reference station parameters (ECEF position)</td><td>Base station location</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Type 9</strong></td><td>High-rate GPS corrections (subset of SVs)</td><td>Partial update at higher rate</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Type 18</strong></td><td>RTK uncorrected carrier phases</td><td>Legacy RTK</td></tr>
            <tr><td><strong>Type 19</strong></td><td>RTK uncorrected pseudoranges</td><td>Legacy RTK</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 4 -->
      <h2 id="rtcm3">RTCM 3.x — the modern standard</h2>
      <p>
        RTCM 3.0 was introduced in 2004 with a completely redesigned binary format. RTCM 3.3
        (2016) added multi-constellation support. RTCM 3.3 Amendment 1 (2018) added SSR messages
        for PPP-RTK. This is the version in active use today.
      </p>
      <p>
        RTCM 3.x message types fall into several families:
      </p>

      <div class="msg-families">
        <div class="family">
          <div class="family-range">1001–1004</div>
          <div class="family-name">GPS RTK observables (legacy format)</div>
          <div class="family-desc">GPS L1/L2 code and phase for RTK. Still widely supported but being replaced by MSM.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="family">
          <div class="family-range">1005–1006</div>
          <div class="family-name">Reference station coordinates</div>
          <div class="family-desc">ECEF position of the base station. Essential — rover needs this to compute the baseline. MT 1006 adds antenna height.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="family">
          <div class="family-range">1007–1008</div>
          <div class="family-name">Antenna descriptor</div>
          <div class="family-desc">Antenna type and serial number. Required for precise work — different antennas have different phase centre offsets.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="family">
          <div class="family-range">1013</div>
          <div class="family-name">System parameters</div>
          <div class="family-desc">Message transmission timing, network ID.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="family">
          <div class="family-range">1071–1077</div>
          <div class="family-name">GPS MSM1–MSM7</div>
          <div class="family-desc">GPS Multiple Signal Messages. MSM4 and MSM7 are the recommended types for modern RTK.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="family">
          <div class="family-range">1081–1087</div>
          <div class="family-name">GLONASS MSM1–MSM7</div>
          <div class="family-desc">GLONASS Multiple Signal Messages.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="family">
          <div class="family-range">1091–1097</div>
          <div class="family-name">Galileo MSM1–MSM7</div>
          <div class="family-desc">Galileo Multiple Signal Messages.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="family">
          <div class="family-range">1121–1127</div>
          <div class="family-name">BeiDou MSM1–MSM7</div>
          <div class="family-desc">BeiDou Multiple Signal Messages.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="family">
          <div class="family-range">1057–1068</div>
          <div class="family-name">GPS SSR messages</div>
          <div class="family-desc">GPS orbit, clock, phase bias, VTEC corrections for PPP-RTK.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="family">
          <div class="family-range">1240–1270</div>
          <div class="family-name">Galileo/GLONASS/BeiDou SSR</div>
          <div class="family-desc">SSR corrections for non-GPS constellations.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 5 -->
      <h2 id="msm">MSM — Multiple Signal Messages</h2>
      <p>
        MSM (Multiple Signal Messages) are the modern RTCM observation format, introduced in
        RTCM 3.2. They replace the older constellation-specific messages (1001–1004 for GPS,
        etc.) with a unified structure that works for any constellation and any signal combination.
      </p>
      <p>
        Each constellation has seven MSM subtypes numbered 1–7, with increasing data content:
      </p>

      <div class="msm-grid">
        <div class="msm-card msm-basic">
          <div class="msm-type">MSM1–3</div>
          <div class="msm-name">Basic</div>
          <div class="msm-content">
            <div class="msm-item">Rough pseudorange only (MSM1)</div>
            <div class="msm-item">Rough pseudorange + phase (MSM2)</div>
            <div class="msm-item">Rough pseudorange + phase + Doppler (MSM3)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="msm-use">Rarely used. Low bandwidth but insufficient for RTK.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="msm-card msm-full">
          <div class="msm-type">MSM4</div>
          <div class="msm-name">Full pseudorange + phase</div>
          <div class="msm-content">
            <div class="msm-item">Full-resolution pseudorange</div>
            <div class="msm-item">Full-resolution carrier phase</div>
            <div class="msm-item">Lock time indicator</div>
            <div class="msm-item">Half-cycle ambiguity indicator</div>
            <div class="msm-item">Signal-to-noise ratio (GNSS SNR)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="msm-use">Standard for most RTK applications. Good balance of data content and bandwidth.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="msm-card msm-extended">
          <div class="msm-type">MSM5–6</div>
          <div class="msm-name">Full + Doppler</div>
          <div class="msm-content">
            <div class="msm-item">All MSM4 fields</div>
            <div class="msm-item">Doppler (MSM5)</div>
            <div class="msm-item">Extended resolution fields (MSM6)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="msm-use">MSM5 when Doppler velocity data is needed. MSM6 for extended precision.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="msm-card msm-max">
          <div class="msm-type">MSM7</div>
          <div class="msm-name">Full + Doppler + extended</div>
          <div class="msm-content">
            <div class="msm-item">All MSM5 fields</div>
            <div class="msm-item">Extended resolution pseudorange</div>
            <div class="msm-item">Extended resolution phase</div>
            <div class="msm-item">Extended resolution SNR</div>
          </div>
          <div class="msm-use">Maximum data content. Required for high-precision PPP post-processing. Higher bandwidth.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-icon">⚡</div>
        <div>
          <strong>Recommended configuration for RTK:</strong> Output MSM4 for GPS, Galileo and
          BeiDou (message types 1074, 1094, 1124) plus MT 1005 (base station coordinates) and
          MT 1230 (GLONASS code-phase biases if using GLONASS). MSM4 is ~50% smaller than MSM7
          while providing all data needed for RTK ambiguity resolution.
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 6 -->
      <h2 id="ssr">SSR — State Space Representation</h2>
      <p>
        SSR messages broadcast individual physical error corrections rather than lumped
        pseudorange corrections. They are the basis for PPP-RTK correction services.
        Unlike MSM (which carries observations), SSR carries <em>corrections to apply to your own observations</em>.
      </p>

      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th>Message</th>
              <th>Content</th>
              <th>Update rate</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>MT 1057 (GPS)</strong><br><small>1240 Galileo, 1258 GLONASS</small></td>
              <td>Orbit corrections — radial, along-track and cross-track corrections to broadcast ephemeris</td>
              <td>5 – 60 s</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>MT 1058 (GPS)</strong><br><small>1241 Galileo, 1259 GLONASS</small></td>
              <td>Clock corrections — c0, c1, c2 polynomial coefficients correcting broadcast clock</td>
              <td>1 – 10 s</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>MT 1059 (GPS)</strong><br><small>1243 Galileo</small></td>
              <td>Code biases — signal-specific code bias corrections (m)</td>
              <td>60 – 120 s</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>MT 1265 (GPS)</strong><br><small>1266 Galileo</small></td>
              <td>Phase biases — uncalibrated phase delay corrections enabling integer ambiguity resolution</td>
              <td>30 – 60 s</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>MT 1264</strong></td>
              <td>VTEC (Vertical Total Electron Content) ionospheric grid corrections</td>
              <td>30 – 300 s</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>MT 4076</strong></td>
              <td>IGS SSR (extended precision orbit, clock and bias corrections)</td>
              <td>1 – 5 s</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 7 -->
      <h2 id="common-messages">Common message reference</h2>
      <p>
        The messages you will most commonly configure, receive or diagnose in an RTK system:
      </p>

      <div class="msg-reference">
        <div class="mr-row mr-header">
          <span>MT</span>
          <span>Name</span>
          <span>Required for</span>
          <span>Typical rate</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mr-row mr-essential">
          <span>1005</span>
          <span>Reference station coordinates (no height)</span>
          <span>All RTK — rover needs base position</span>
          <span>0.1 Hz</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mr-row mr-essential">
          <span>1006</span>
          <span>Reference station coordinates + antenna height</span>
          <span>All RTK when antenna ARP matters</span>
          <span>0.1 Hz</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mr-row">
          <span>1007</span>
          <span>Antenna descriptor</span>
          <span>Precise survey (phase centre correction)</span>
          <span>0.1 Hz</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mr-row mr-essential">
          <span>1074</span>
          <span>GPS MSM4</span>
          <span>GPS RTK observations</span>
          <span>1 Hz</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mr-row mr-essential">
          <span>1094</span>
          <span>Galileo MSM4</span>
          <span>Galileo RTK observations</span>
          <span>1 Hz</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mr-row mr-essential">
          <span>1124</span>
          <span>BeiDou MSM4</span>
          <span>BeiDou RTK observations</span>
          <span>1 Hz</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mr-row">
          <span>1084</span>
          <span>GLONASS MSM4</span>
          <span>GLONASS RTK (if using GLONASS)</span>
          <span>1 Hz</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mr-row">
          <span>1230</span>
          <span>GLONASS code-phase biases</span>
          <span>Required for GLONASS RTK accuracy</span>
          <span>0.1 Hz</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mr-row">
          <span>1077</span>
          <span>GPS MSM7</span>
          <span>High-precision PPP post-processing</span>
          <span>1 Hz</span>
        </div>
        <div class="mr-row">
          <span>1033</span>
          <span>Receiver and antenna descriptor</span>
          <span>Network logging, quality control</span>
          <span>0.1 Hz</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 8 -->
      <h2 id="choosing">Choosing which messages to output</h2>
      <p>
        When configuring a base station, the choice of RTCM messages depends on your application:
      </p>

      <div class="config-grid">
        <div class="config-card">
          <div class="config-title">Minimum RTK (GPS+Galileo)</div>
          <div class="config-msgs">
            <span class="msg-badge essential">MT 1005</span>
            <span class="msg-badge essential">MT 1074</span>
            <span class="msg-badge essential">MT 1094</span>
          </div>
          <div class="config-bw">~500 bytes/s at 1 Hz</div>
          <div class="config-desc">Sufficient for single-baseline RTK with GPS and Galileo. Works on 9600 bps radio modem.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="config-card">
          <div class="config-title">Full multi-constellation RTK</div>
          <div class="config-msgs">
            <span class="msg-badge essential">MT 1006</span>
            <span class="msg-badge essential">MT 1074</span>
            <span class="msg-badge essential">MT 1084</span>
            <span class="msg-badge essential">MT 1094</span>
            <span class="msg-badge essential">MT 1124</span>
            <span class="msg-badge">MT 1230</span>
          </div>
          <div class="config-bw">~1200 bytes/s at 1 Hz</div>
          <div class="config-desc">GPS + GLONASS + Galileo + BeiDou. Maximum satellite count, fastest TTFF. Needs cellular or high-rate radio.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="config-card">
          <div class="config-title">PPP post-processing quality</div>
          <div class="config-msgs">
            <span class="msg-badge essential">MT 1006</span>
            <span class="msg-badge essential">MT 1007</span>
            <span class="msg-badge essential">MT 1077</span>
            <span class="msg-badge essential">MT 1097</span>
            <span class="msg-badge essential">MT 1127</span>
          </div>
          <div class="config-bw">~2000 bytes/s at 1 Hz</div>
          <div class="config-desc">MSM7 for extended resolution. Required for submitting to CORS networks and PPP post-processing services.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- SECTION 9 - SUMMARY -->
      <h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
      <div class="summary-grid">
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📦</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Binary and compact</div>
          <div class="summary-body">RTCM is binary — not human-readable. Designed for bandwidth-constrained links. A complete MSM4 epoch for 10 satellites is ~150 bytes vs ~800 bytes for equivalent NMEA.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">📡</div>
          <div class="summary-title">MSM4 for RTK</div>
          <div class="summary-body">MSM4 (MT 1074/1084/1094/1124) is the standard for modern multi-constellation RTK. Always pair with MT 1005/1006 for base station coordinates.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">🌐</div>
          <div class="summary-title">SSR for PPP-RTK</div>
          <div class="summary-body">SSR messages (MT 1057–1068, 1240–1270) broadcast individual error corrections for PPP-RTK. Different concept from MSM — corrections to apply, not observations to difference.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="summary-card">
          <div class="summary-icon">✅</div>
          <div class="summary-title">Always validate CRC</div>
          <div class="summary-body">CRC-24Q is mandatory. Never process RTCM frames without checking the CRC. Radio links, particularly UHF, produce corrupt frames regularly.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="nav-footer">
        <a href="/learn/protocols/rinex" class="nav-prev">← RINEX</a>
        <a href="/learn/protocols/ntrip" class="nav-next">NTRIP →</a>
      </div>

      <div class="references" id="references">
        <h3>References and further reading</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>RTCM 10403.3 — Differential GNSS (Global Navigation Satellite Systems) Services – Version 3. <a href="https://www.rtcm.org/differential-gnss-standards" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">rtcm.org →</a></li>
          <li>RTCM 10410.1 — RTCM Standard for Networked Transport of RTCM via Internet Protocol (Ntrip), Version 2.0.</li>
          <li>Wübbena, G., Schmitz, M. & Bagge, A. (2005). PPP-RTK: Precise point positioning using state-space representation in RTK networks. <em>ION GNSS 2005</em>.</li>
          <li>u-blox Application Note: RTCM 3 Configuration. <a href="https://www.u-blox.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">u-blox.com →</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>

    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>

<style>
  .learn-container { max-width: 820px; }
  .breadcrumb { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 8px; font-size: 13px; color: var(--text3); margin-bottom: 28px; flex-wrap: wrap; }
  .breadcrumb a { color: var(--text2); transition: color 0.2s; }
  .breadcrumb a:hover { color: var(--accent); }
  .article-header { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  h1 { font-size: clamp(24px, 4vw, 38px); font-weight: 700; margin: 10px 0 16px; line-height: 1.2; }
  h2 { font-size: 22px; font-weight: 700; margin: 40px 0 16px; padding-top: 8px; border-top: 1px solid var(--border); }
  .lead { font-size: 17px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 12px; max-width: 720px; }
  .article-meta { font-size: 12px; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); display: flex; gap: 8px; }
  p { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  ul { font-size: 15px; color: var(--text2); line-height: 1.8; padding-left: 24px; margin-bottom: 16px; }
  li { margin-bottom: 6px; }
  strong { color: var(--text); font-weight: 600; }
  a { color: var(--accent2); text-decoration: underline; text-underline-offset: 2px; }
  code { font-family: var(--mono); font-size: 13px; background: var(--bg3); padding: 1px 5px; border-radius: 3px; color: var(--accent2); }
  em { font-style: italic; }
  small { font-size: 11px; color: var(--text3); display: block; margin-top: 2px; }

  .toc { background: var(--bg2); border: 1px solid var(--border); border-radius: 10px; padding: 20px 24px; margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .toc-title { font-size: 11px; font-weight: 600; letter-spacing: 0.1em; text-transform: uppercase; color: var(--text3); font-family: var(--mono); margin-bottom: 10px; }
  .toc ol { margin: 0; padding-left: 18px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 6px; }
  .toc li { font-size: 14px; }
  .toc a { color: var(--text2); text-decoration: none; }
  .toc a:hover { color: var(--accent); }

  .callout { display: flex; gap: 14px; padding: 16px 20px; border-radius: 10px; margin: 24px 0; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.7; }
  .callout-icon { font-size: 18px; flex-shrink: 0; }
  .callout-info { background: rgba(0,153,255,0.06); border: 1px solid rgba(0,153,255,0.18); color: var(--text2); }
